Comment
Commented
j. von Hettlingen
JUN 23, 2017


                Richard N. Haass laments that America under Trump is abandoning its role as  guarantor of  the current global world order  -  a role "that has defined its foreign policy for three quarters of a century, under Democratic and Republican presidents alike." That order has enabled 70 years of prosperity, thanks to market-oriented regimes of trade liberalisation, increased capital mobility, and appropriate social welfare policies. Countries in Europe, the Middle East, and Asia have been able to share America's security umbrella - through Nato and various other alliances.Trump sees foreign policy and trade through the prism of his  'America first' approach. While slashing the budget for foreign policy and agencies that promote soft power, he has increased military spending. He is  making America's decades-old allies to foot their defence bill, and has threatened to impose punitive tariffs to tackle trade deficits. He blames the loss of jobs and falling incomes on foreign competition and globalisation. He doesn't believe in climate change, and ditched  the Paris Agreement, in an effort to re-open mines and explore gas- and oil fields.  But history had taught us a lesson that  nativism, protectionism and isolationism are a toxic mix for economic and military disaster. The author - a neo-con foreign policy wonk - says a vacuum emerges with "a shift away from a US-dominated world of structured relationships and standing institutions." It is still too early to discern "what this alternative will be." It is true that "there is no alternative great power willing and able to step in and assume what had been the US role." The EU is America's oldest ally, but it is far from being strong to lead the world. In fact without active US engagement in Europe, an aggressively revanchist Russia will step in, even though its "narrowly-based economy" is struggling. Western-led anctions and falling energy prices have taken a heavy toll on Russia's economy, but it doesn't deter Putin from staging a return to global power, focusing on Europe and the Middle East. China is seen as the only power that can challenge America's leadership. But it is "focused mostly on consolidating domestic order and maintaining artificially high economic-growth rates to stave off popular unrest. China’s interest in regional and global institutions seems designed mostly to bolster its economy and geopolitical influence, rather than to help set rules and create broadly beneficial arrangements." Beijing welcomed Trump's leaving the Trans-Pacific Partnership to expand its influence in the region. But. China will unlikely "use its influence to restrain North Korea," because it needs it as a buffer state between South Korea and its border. Despite huge influence on Pakistan, it's reluctant to help India and Pakistan reconcile. India has border disputes with both China  and Pakistan. The South China Sea is also another venue of territorial disputes between China and the littoral countries there.If the US gives up on its Asian allies such as the Philippines, South Korea, and Taiwan, those countries may have no choice but to submit themselves to Beijing. Other US allies, such as Japan and India, may be forced to militarise and challenge China openly. Thus, an American withdrawal from the region could very well eventually bring on a military conflict there.The Middle East with its pertual conflicts sparked by the Shia/Sunni schism, pits the Shia-majority Iran against the Saudi-led Sunni coalition. Africa has been plagued by drought, population explosion, and the corrupt regimes have failed to address the social-economic woes, that easily lead to violence.The author points out that people, despite criticising the US "for what it was and what it was not," will one day look back with fondness the global order the America has secured. "They face the prospect of a world in which American leadership is likely to be less of a factor. It is far from clear that they are prepared for such a world, or that they will find themselves better off in it."  Read more








