Reply

Comment
Commented
S.Mahmud Ali
JUN 22, 2017


                Dr Haass, a prominent US practitioner-turned-strategist, lays out the challenges flowing out of systemic transitional fluidity. However, the suggestion that the US-designed-and-led liberal order has been in place 'for three quarters of a century' ignores the fact that such an order has been much more shortlived than that. The USA, with the help of its allies and partners in the Second World War - which, incidentally, included Stalin's USSR and Chiang Kai-shek's China - established a multilateralist and collegial system of collective global governance via the San Francisco Conferences starting in late-1945. The UN, especially the UNSC and its veto-wielding P5 at its core - were fashioned to collaboratively manage the planet's post-War problems. But as the USA and the USSR charted their national-interest-focused and ideologically-driven courses, the P5 was much less effective than its early promise. The bipolarity cleaving the systemic core, formalised by NSC69 and the Korean War, ensured there were at least two hemispheric orders - the US-led capitalist West and the Soviet-led communist/socialist East, each challenging the other's leadership and reducing the planet to a battleground for their competing ideals and interests, with the world perennially shivering on the brink of thermonuclear catastrophe. The US-led OECD was the dominant political-economic aggregation of power in the world, but it only covered a small part of the planet. There was no world order for the US to lead until 1991.Soviet evisceration, effected via clandestine Sino-US strategic collaboration in Central America, Southern Africa and the Horn, South Asia, Indochina and, most spectacularly, Afghanistan, supplanted bipolarity at the systemic core with unipolarity. Although large swathes of the world's surface remained beyond its  ken, this post-Soviet era could accurately be generalised as the US-led liberal world order. But such orders last only as long as major players acquiesce in it and accept their own subordination to the primate. In late 1993, when the CPCCC and the CMC jointly identified the USA, Japan and the RoK as the source of the most acute threats to Chinese security, and began preparing to deter intervention, that voluntary subordination ended. In 1999, the DoD/ONA Summer Study similarly identified China as a 'constant competitor' and later, viewing it as a 'near-peer rival', America prepared to neutralise Chinese challenges to US primacy. By definition, the system was no longer unipolar. In a non-unipolar system, again by definition, there simply could not be a 'global order'. This is why it would be logical to state that the US-designed-and-led order acquired and retained its (virtually) global character between the end of 1991 when the USSR collapsed and the summer of 1993 when Beijing began girding itself against the systemic primate, and certainly by the end of 1999, when the Executive and Legislative Branches in Washington took policy-measures against China's challenges to American primacy, the 'globality' of the US-led order ended.So, when eminent analysts premise their analyses on assertions of a very shortlived US-led order as the global norm, then all inferences flowing from such analyses must, logically, be much more imperfect than the simple frailties of human cognition would warrant. This would be a difficult methodology for delivering practical policy options. Read more








